2 Sec. 1. 5 MRSA §200-O is enacted to read:
3 §200-O. Maine Nonprofit Security Grant Program
4 1. Definitions. As used in this section, unless the context otherwise indicates, the
5 following terms have the following meanings.
6 A. "Hate crime" means a crime in which the perpetrator selected the victim or the
7 property that was damaged or otherwise affected by the crime because of the race,
8 color, religion, sex, ancestry, national origin, physical or mental disability, sexual
9 orientation, gender identity or homelessness of the victim or of the owner or occupant
10 of that property.
11 B. "Program" means the Maine Nonprofit Security Grant Program established in
12 subsection 2.
13 C. "Serious bodily injury" has the same meaning as in Title 17-A, section 2, subsection
14 23.
15 D. "Terror attack" means an attack that causes serious bodily injury or death to multiple
16 persons or causes substantial damage to a structure and is made for the purpose of
17 intimidating or coercing a civilian population or to affect the conduct of government.
18 2. Program established. The Maine Nonprofit Security Grant Program is established
19 in the Office of the Attorney General to provide grants to assist nonprofit organizations to
20 improve security at property owned or occupied by those nonprofit organizations to protect
21 against hate crimes and terror attacks.
22 3. Eligibility. To be eligible for a grant from the program, a nonprofit organization
23 must:
24 A. Be a tax-exempt organization under 26 United States Code, Section 501(c)(3); and
25 B. Demonstrate that the organization or the organization's facilities are at high risk of
26 a hate crime or terror attack.
27 4. Use of grants. A nonprofit organization awarded a grant from the program shall
28 use that grant for:
29 A. Physical security enhancements;
30 B. The cost of security personnel; or
31 C. The development or enhancement of security plans and protocols.
32 5. Administration. The Office of the Attorney General shall administer the program
33 and shall develop guidelines and criteria to award grants to eligible nonprofit organizations
34 under subsection 3 using a request for proposals process.
35 6. Rules. The Office of the Attorney General may adopt routine technical rules as
36 described in Title 5, chapter 375, subchapter 2-A to implement this section.
